<@2> Introduction | introduction </@2>


<p>
  This is a passage written by
  <@>
    趙元任<^> Cheeu Yu"n-yam | Chao Yu"an-je^n | Zhao Yuanren </^>
    | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yuen_Ren_Chao
    | Wikipedia: Yuen Ren Chao
  </@>,
  a Chinese-American linguist, etc.
  It is written in literary Chinese, with every character pronounced
  尸 (<^e>shi</^e>) up to tone in Mandarin.
</p>

<p>
  Mandarin has a higher rate of homophones than say Cantonese,
  due to loss of entering tone among other phonological shifts.
  To recap, 四聲,
  or the <b>four classical tone classes</b> of Chinese, are:
</p>

<ol>
  <li>平~(level)</li>
  <li>上~(rising)</li>
  <li>去~(departing)</li>
  <li>入~(entering)</li>
</ol>

<p>
  These are <strong>not</strong> the four tones of modern Mandarin.
  Although modern Mandarin numerically has four tones,
  they only fall under the first three classical tone classes:
</p>

<ol>
  <li>陰平~(dark level)</li>
  <li>陽平~(light level)</li>
  <li>上~(rising)</li>
  <li>去~(departing)</li>
</ol>

<p>
  From the perspective of Western linguistics,
  <@>
    entering tones
    | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checked_tone
    | Wikipedia: Checked tone
  </@>
  are not separate tones because they are syllables which
  end abruptly in <span class="no-wrapping">-p</span>,
  <span class="no-wrapping">-t</span> or <span class="no-wrapping">-k</span>.
  However, the distinction is important in Chinese poetry,
  where balancing 平聲 (level tone) and 仄聲 (sloping tone, i.e.~上去入)
  is highly desirable.
  Historically, Mandarin and other northern varieties of Chinese
  underwent 入派三聲;
  after losing the ending consonants <span class="no-wrapping">-p</span>,
  <span class="no-wrapping">-t</span> and <span class="no-wrapping">-k</span>,
  entering tone words were redistributed amongst the other three tones.
  To give a contrived example,
</p>
<#c>
  實食十石時
</#c>
<p>
  meaning "{it's} really time {to} eat ten stones",
  reads in Mandarin
</p>
<#c>
  <^e>shi/ shi/ shi/ shi/ shi/</^e>
</#c>
<p>
  but in Cantonese
</p>
<#c>
  <^e>shat9 shik9 shap9 shek9 shee4</^e>.
</#c>

<p>
  Now 趙元任<^> Cheeu Yu"n-yam | Chao Yu"an-je^n | Zhao Yuanren </^>
  did not write 《施氏食獅史》 to compare the phonologies of Cantonese and Mandarin,
  but to demonstrate (with an extreme example) why literary Chinese
  should not be romanised.
  In any regional variant, Literary Chinese is a language
  to be read and comprehended with the eyes, rather than heard with the ears,
  though it may still be read aloud.
  (Romanising vernacular Chinese, however, is all right.
  趙元任<^> Cheeu Yu"n-yam | Chao Yu"an-je^n | Zhao Yuanren </^>
  and others developed
  <@>
    "Gwoyeu Romatzyh"
    | https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gwoyeu_Romatzyh
    | Wikipedia: Gwoyeu Romatzyh
  </@>,
  a romanisation system for Mandarin which uses spelling,
  rather than diacritics, to indicate different tones.)
</p>


